  "prompt": "Who discovered Avogadro's number?",
  "response": "Avogadro's number, also known as Avogadro's constant, was not directly discovered by one individual but is named after the Italian scientist Amedeo Avogadro. Avogadro proposed that equal volumes of gases, at the same temperature and pressure, contain an equal number of molecules. This hypothesis, known as Avogadro's hypothesis, laid the groundwork for the concept of the mole and Avogadro's number.\n\nThe actual determination of the numerical value of Avogadro's number was accomplished through various experiments and calculations by multiple scientists over time. Key contributors include Johann Josef Loschmidt, who made early estimates of the size of molecules, and Jean Perrin, who used experimental data on Brownian motion to estimate the number. The constant is now defined as exactly 6.02214076 \u00d7 10\u00b2\u00b3 entities per mole, based on the 2019 redefinition of the SI base units.",
